The default request size is 4MB, you could get it here: [support request File Upload utility guidelines][1]. So you have to increase that limit if you want to allow uploading and downloading of larger files.

You could set `maxRequestLength` and `maxAllowedContentLength` values in your `web.config` file.

Here is a sample web.config.

    &lt;?xml version=&quot;1.0&quot; encoding=&quot;utf-8&quot;?&gt;
    &lt;configuration&gt;
    &lt;system.web&gt;
        &lt;!-- 100 MB in kilobytes --&gt;
        &lt;httpRuntime maxRequestLength=&quot;204800&quot; /&gt;
    &lt;/system.web&gt;

    &lt;system.webServer&gt;
        &lt;security&gt;
            &lt;requestFiltering&gt;
                &lt;!-- 100 MB in bytes --&gt;
                &lt;requestLimits maxAllowedContentLength=&quot;209715200&quot; /&gt;
            &lt;/requestFiltering&gt;
        &lt;/security&gt;
    &lt;/system.webServer&gt;
&lt;/configuration&gt;

Further more information, you could refer to this blog:[Upload Large File In asp.net or website in Windows Azure][2] .

And beside this, you could choose to upload file to Azure Storage to handle large files. This is about using [Web API and Azure Blob][3].


